    "kicker": "Things to consider · before you commit",
    "title_html": "Three things <em>most</em> homeowners forget.",
    "items": [
      {
        "number": "01.",
        "heading": "Ranch architecture lives or dies by the roof line.",
        "body": "Ranch architecture lives or dies by the roof line. A long, low ranch with a poorly-chosen roof color reads as dated 1960s suburbia; the same ranch with a modern roof color refresh (charcoal or black) reads as deliberate mid-century revival. The roof color choice on a ranch is the highest-impact single update available."
      },
      {
        "number": "02.",
        "heading": "Charcoal is the safest mid-tone roof for resale.",
        "body": "Charcoal is the single most-installed asphalt color in the architectural category nationally, which means it appeals to the widest pool of resale buyers and translates across most home styles. If you are not strongly committed to a more decisive color (true black, weathered wood), charcoal is the lowest-risk choice."
      },
      {
        "number": "03.",
        "heading": "Install quality matters more than SKU.",
        "body": "All seven recommended SKUs hit Class A fire and 110-150 mph wind ratings. The bigger variable on a ranch elevation is install quality: ridge-line straightness, valley flashing, starter strip alignment. Insist on a Master Elite or equivalent certified contractor and a written workmanship warranty separate from the manufacturer's material warranty."
      }
    ]
